### Typedef Basics

Typedefs create aliases for function types, improving code readability and reusability.

```dart
// Define a function type alias
typedef IntOperation = int Function(int a, int b);

int add(int a, int b) => a + b;
int multiply(int a, int b) => a * b;

void execute(IntOperation op, int x, int y) {
  print('Result: ${op(x, y)}');
}

void main() {
  execute(add, 5, 3);      // Result: 8
  execute(multiply, 5, 3); // Result: 15
}
```

### Typedef with Parameters

```dart
typedef Filter = bool Function(String item);
typedef Transformer = String Function(String item);
typedef Callback = void Function(String message);

List<String> filterList(List<String> items, Filter filter) {
  return items.where(filter).toList();
}

List<String> transformList(List<String> items, Transformer transform) {
  return items.map(transform).toList();
}

void main() {
  var names = ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie', 'Dave'];

  var longNames = filterList(names, (name) => name.length > 3);
  print(longNames); // [Alice, Charlie, Dave]

  var upperNames = transformList(names, (name) => name.toUpperCase());
  print(upperNames); // [ALICE, BOB, CHARLIE, DAVE]
}
```

### Typedef in Classes

```dart
typedef EventHandler = void Function(Map<String, dynamic> event);

class EventBus {
  final List<EventHandler> _handlers = [];

  void addHandler(EventHandler handler) {
    _handlers.add(handler);
  }

  void emit(Map<String, dynamic> event) {
    for (var handler in _handlers) {
      handler(event);
    }
  }
}

void main() {
  var bus = EventBus();
  bus.addHandler((event) => print('Received: $event'));
  bus.emit({'type': 'login', 'user': 'alice'});
}
```

### Typedef for Generic Functions

```dart
typedef Comparator<T> = int Function(T a, T b);
typedef Mapper<T, R> = R Function(T input);

void sortWithComparator<T>(List<T> items, Comparator<T> compare) {
  items.sort(compare);
}

List<R> mapList<T, R>(List<T> items, Mapper<T, R> mapper) {
  return items.map(mapper).toList();
}

void main() {
  var numbers = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9];
  sortWithComparator<int>(numbers, (a, b) => a - b);
  print(numbers); // [1, 1, 3, 4, 5, 9]

  var doubled = mapList<int, int>(numbers, (n) => n * 2);
  print(doubled);
}
```

### Benefits of Typedef

| Benefit | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Readability | Descriptive names for complex types |
| Reusability | Single definition used everywhere |
| Maintainability | Change one place, update all |
| Documentation | Self-documenting intent |

> **Key Point:** Use typedef to give meaningful names to function types. This makes your code more self-documenting and reduces duplication of complex type signatures.

